Radio telescopes:

In radio astronomy, the most powerful telescope in the world is the Robert C. Byrd Green Bank Telescope (GBT), located in West Virginia, USA. Byrd GBT has a collecting area of 27,000 square kilometres (11,000 square miles). This makes it much larger than any other radio telescope on the planet.

The telescope is also quite special. It is designed to look at incredibly small parts of the sky, called "sub-millimeter bands". This means that it can detect very faint sources of radio waves, such as exoplanets (planets orbiting other stars), pulsars, and active galaxies.


